{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628840"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:02:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:02:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17245"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17245"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.05,0.21,0.26,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9935"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69613"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9935"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17245"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55066"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"3898"},{"type":"tags","id":"3899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10773"},{"type":"tags","id":"10776"},{"type":"tags","id":"11066"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23322"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69613"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBRCA1 and BRCA2 are important tumour suppressor genes that help repair damaged DNA. Inherited mutations in these genes significantly increase cancer risk, including breast cancer and several other cancer types.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cancers is most strongly associated with inherited BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroid cancer","Bladder cancer","Pancreatic cancer","Lung cancer","Colorectal cancer"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAfter breast and ovarian cancer, \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatic cancer\u003C/strong\u003E shows a significant association with BRCA mutations. The lifetime risk of pancreatic cancer is increased 2-6 fold in BRCA mutation carriers, particularly those with BRCA2 mutations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid cancer\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ebladder cancer\u003C/strong\u003E are not significantly associated with BRCA mutations\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily associated with environmental factors rather than hereditary mutations\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColorectal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E has a weak association with BRCA mutations; Lynch syndrome is the main hereditary syndrome for colorectal cancer\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther cancers strongly associated with BRCA mutations include breast cancer (highest risk), ovarian cancer, and prostate cancer (particularly BRCA2). The risk varies depending on which gene is affected and the specific mutation involved.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations increase risk of breast, ovarian, prostate, and pancreatic cancers","BRCA1 and BRCA2 are tumor suppressor genes involved in DNA repair through homologous recombination","The pattern of inheritance for BRCA mutations is autosomal dominant"],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Gene